{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Tarzan's Quest | title_orig = | translator = | image = Tarzans quest.jpg | caption = Dust-jacket illustration of ''Tarzan's Quest'' | author = [[Edgar Rice Burroughs]] | illustrator = [[J. Allen St. John]] | cover_artist = | country = [[United States]] | language = [[English language|English]] | series = Tarzan series | genre = [[Adventure novel|Adventure]] | publisher = [[Edgar Rice Burroughs, Inc.]] | release_date = 1936 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]]) | pages = 318 | preceded_by = [[Tarzan and the Leopard Men]] | followed_by = [[Tarzan and the Forbidden City]] }} '''''Tarzan's Quest''''' is a novel by American writer [[Edgar Rice Burroughs]], the nineteenth in his series of books about the title character [[Tarzan]]. Originally serialized in six parts, as ''Tarzan and the Immortal Men'', in ''The Blue Book Magazine'', from October 1935 to March 1936; the first collected edition was published as the 1936 novel ''Tarzan’s Quest'' by Burroughs’ own publishing company.
==Plot== Tarzan's wife [[Jane Porter (Tarzan)|Jane]] (her first appearance since ''[[Tarzan and the Ant Men]]'' and also her last as a major character in the series), becomes involved in a search for a bloodthirsty lost tribe reputed to possess an immortality drug. Also drawn in are Tarzan and his monkey companion, little [[Nkima]], and Chief [[Muviro]] and his faithful [[Waziri (fictional tribe)|Waziri]] warriors, who are searching for Muviro's lost daughter Buira. Nkima's vital contribution to the adventure is recognized when he is made a recipient of the immortality treatment along with the human protagonists at the end of the novel.
==Comic adaptations== The book has been adapted into [[Tarzan (comics)|comic]] form by [[Gold Key Comics]] in ''Tarzan'' nos. 188–189, dated October–December 1969.
